<h2>
    <strong>Licenses and Regulations You Need to Know</strong>
</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife Rules</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Before casting your line, it's crucial to check the current regulations set by the <strong>Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife (ODFW)</strong>. Chum salmon fishing near Gresham is subject to seasonal and location-based restrictions, often changing yearly to protect the population.
</p>
<p>
    Anglers aged 12 and older must have a valid Oregon fishing license. Additionally, a Combined Angling Tag is required for salmon fishing, along with a Columbia River Basin Endorsement if you plan to fish in tributaries connected to the Columbia River.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Daily Bag Limits and Legal Gear</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Regulations typically limit the number of chum salmon you can keep per day. The current rule (as of 2024) generally allows <strong>one or two salmon per day</strong>, but always verify this with the ODFW’s online regulation updates.
</p>
<p>
    Legal gear includes single-point barbless hooks and artificial lures or bait. Snagging is strictly prohibited, and ethical angling methods are encouraged to minimize fish stress and injury.
</p>
<h2>
    <strong>Essential Gear for Chum Salmon Fishing</strong>
</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>Rods, Reels, and Lines</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Chum salmon are strong fighters, so a <strong>medium-heavy spinning or baitcasting rod</strong> (8 to 10 feet long) is ideal. Match it with a quality reel that can hold at least 150 yards of <strong>15-30 lb test line</strong>.
</p>
<p>
    Braided line offers strength and sensitivity, while a fluorocarbon leader helps maintain stealth in clear waters.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Recommended Bait and Lures</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Chum salmon are aggressive during spawning, responding well to brightly colored lures like pink, chartreuse, or purple. Effective options include:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Corkies and yarn combos
    </li>
    <li>
        Twitching jigs
    </li>
    <li>
        Spinners (like Blue Fox or Mepps)
    </li>
    <li>
        Cured salmon eggs or shrimp
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Experimenting with scent attractants can also improve your success rate.
</p>
